	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Trade policy and the development of a new integrated poultry operation in Namibia</h1>

			
			<h4>
												12 November 2011
										</h4>

						<h2>An interview with Ghys White, General Manager of Namib Poultry Industries</h2>
					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						
<div class="object-left">		
<div class="embed-image">
<img border="0" src="/var/agritrade/storage/images/gys-white/510330-1-eng-GB/Gys-White_medium.jpg" width="200" height="134"></div></div><p>Ghys White is the General Manager of Namib Poultry Industries (Pty) Ltd. He has been responsible for the planning and implementation of the construction of the first new fully integrated chicken breeder, hatchery, broiler and abattoir operation in Namibia. Before joining Namib Poultry Industries, he was responsible for the planning and implementation of a similar fully integrated chicken breeder, hatchery, broiler and abattoir operation in South Africa.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p><b>Q. What level of national poultry consumption is met from national poultry production?</b></p><p>Currently almost all poultry sold by the retail trade in Namibia is imported from South Africa. It is this reality which our current investments intend to address. It is our aim to supply the full Namibian market – currently estimated at 250,000 chickens per week, or a per capita consumption of 8 kg a year – from national production.</p><p>Indeed, with domestic demand for poultry meat expanding, there is no reason why domestic production should not be further expanded in line with rising domestic demand, once this initial target has been met.</p><p><b>Q. In which components of national poultry markets do imports pose the greatest competitive challenge to national poultry producers?</b></p><p>There is considerable concern in Namibia, and indeed, across the region, over the dumping of cheap poultry parts produced overseas in South America. Indeed, Namibia finds itself bracketed between two of the major African markets targeted by South American poultry exports. These poultry parts are landed at prices lower than the actual production cost of producing the chicken and, given the volumes involved, can seriously disrupt local markets, including in Namibia.</p><p>This dumping of poultry parts can be seen as a major challenge which undermines the competitiveness of poultry production across the Southern African region.</p><p><b>Q. What tariff measures does the government currently have in place to support the national poultry sector?</b></p><p>Currently under the relevant provisions of the SACU agreement, the Namibian poultry sector can invoke infant industry protection provisions. This would mean that once production starts in March 2012, a 46% levy could be charged up to March 2016, after which it would be reduced, first to 30% until 2018 and subsequently 20% until March 2020, after which point it would be phased out.</p><p>The invocation of safeguard provisions is seen as essential in view of the establishment costs, the problems faced from the dumping of poultry parts, and the highly competitive nature of larger-scale producers.</p><p>Since the aim is for Namibia to become independent in poultry production, we would like to see the government introduce a quota system to manage imports, such that imports would only be allowed within the scope of the shortfall in domestic production relative to expanding national demand.</p><p><b>Q. How dependent is the poultry sector on imported feedstocks, day-old chicks, veterinary medicines etc.?</b></p><p>Efforts are under way to address the problems of import dependence in the poultry sector faced elsewhere, by developing an integrated production system.</p><p>Within the same corporate group – through our sister company Voermeester – plans are under way to expand poultry feed production, although this will remain reliant on imports of soya and yellow maize.</p><p>Investment is also under way to establish our own breeder operation, which will produce enough chicks to meet our own production needs.</p><p>There will of course remain an ongoing dependence on the import of registered and prescribed veterinary medicines, which are essential to the maintenance of the health of broiler flocks and the reduction of mortality rates. The use of such medicines will be wholly in line with international best practice.</p><p><b>Q. What are the major challenges in promoting poultry sector development?</b></p><p>There are three main challenges. The first is dealing with rapidly rising global prices for the raw materials used in poultry production – this and the prospect of the emergence of an absolute scarcity is a major source of concern in the longer term.</p><p>It is however also an important motivating factor behind the push for a coherent national poultry sector policy, which promotes national poultry production.</p><p>The second major challenge is the shortcomings in the national network of cold stores, which are essential to the distribution of fresh and chilled poultry products. This requires a supportive investment climate.</p><p>Finally there is the challenge of recruiting and retaining skilled people in a very specialised industry which has never been developed to this level of sophistication in Namibia before.</p><p>These are the reasons why we would like see the government adopt a supporting tariff policy to actively promote the development of the poultry sector. We would also like to see the government facilitate the granting of work permits in specialised fields, to support the necessary transfer of skills over a 5- to 8-year period.</p>
		
		
		
		
		
